Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

Tmdb Movie Data is a collection of films and their details like cast crew, directors etc. The dataset contains 10865 films released between the year 1960 and 2015.

Below is a list of columns and their description:

Column Name Description Used ? Multiple Values ?
id Unique dataset identifier Yes No
imdb_id IDDB unique identifier. Can be used to join to imdb data No No
popular Movie popularity rating Yes No
budget Cost used to produce film Yes No
revenue Sales amount made when movies are sold / rented Yes No
original_title Initial title used for the Movie. No No
cast Actors/Perfomers in the film No Yes (|)
homepage Link to movie homepage No No
director A person who directs how actors perform assigned roles. Yes Yes (|)
tagline One sentence catchphrase No No
keywords Movie metadata/tags No Yes (|)
overview Short description about the film. No No
runtime Length of the Movie in Minutes. No Yes (|)
genres Genre categories which the film falls into. No Yes (|)
production_companies Companies that produced the film. No Yes (|)
release_date The date when film was released. Format MM/DD/YY. Yes No
vote_count Number of Votes Yes No
vote_average Vote average No No
release_year Year Movie was released. No No
budget_adj budget adjested to inflation to reflect 2010 dollars No No
revenue_adj revenue adjusted to reflect dollar values in 2010. No No

Question(s) for Analysis¶

  1. Which Months are best/worst to release a Movie?
  2. Which Directors can deliver best performing movies ?

Replace zero(0) values with mean of the column.¶

Whenever we have zero value in any numeric column, the code below will substitute it with the mean of the column.

In [11]:
# List from dataset with numeric values
numeric_val_list = ['popularity', 'budget', 'revenue', 'vote_count', 'vote_average', 'budget_adj', 'revenue_adj']

def replace_zero_with_mean(lst):
    """
        Replace zero values on the dataframe with the mean values.
        
        Input:
            lst list - List of columns with numeric values in the DataFrame
            
    """
    
    # Iterate over list and replace zero values with mean of the column
    for col_name in lst:
        col_name_mean = df[col_name].mean(skipna=True)
        df[col_name].replace(0, col_name_mean, inplace=True)
    
def check_for_zeros(lst):
    """
        Check for zero values in the Dataframe for columns provided
        
        Input:
            lst list - List of columns with numeric values in the DataFrame
    """
    
    # Iterate over the list and check if zero value exists
    for col_name in lst:
        zero_val_lst = []
        if df[df[col_name] == 0].shape[0] > 0:            
            zero_val_lst.append(col_name)
        
    if len(zero_val_lst) == 0:
        print('No zero value in the list ')
    else:
        print('Zero values present in the columns: {}'.format(zero_val_lst))
    
# Check columns with zero values
check_for_zeros(numeric_val_list)

#Replace zero values with mean
replace_zero_with_mean(numeric_val_list)

# Check to confirm zero values have been replaced
check_for_zeros(numeric_val_list)

Which Month has high performing Movies ?¶

Within the year, some months have high number of holiday days which means people have extra time to devote to leisure activities. In this analysis, I will try to depict months with high movie performance which can be used to guide movie producers to target their release circle around these months.

Movie performance can be measured in terms of high revenues, low buget, high popularity etc

Calculating mean of numeric columns grouped by month. This will allow plotting monthly visualizations for comparison month on month. The resulting data is stored in a new DataFrame (df1). This Dataframe will be used throughout this section.

In [18]:
# Columns with numeric values
cols = ['director', 'popularity', 'budget', 'revenue', 'vote_count', 'vote_average', 'budget_adj', 'revenue_adj', 'profit']

df1 = df.groupby(['month_name', 'month'], as_index=False)[cols].mean()

# Sort DataFrame by month
df1.sort_values(by='month', inplace=True)

From the graph below, the months of May to July and November to Dec have high budget spending. Similarly, low budget is observed in the months of January, August, September and October.

This analysis can be used to guide on which months movies can be produced the cheapest.

In [19]:
ax = df1.plot.area('month_name', 'budget', title='Budget average per month', color='#dadada', figsize=(12,7));

ax.set_xlabel('Month')
ax.set_ylabel('Budget');

In the month of May to July and November to December revenue and profit is at the highest. The months of January and September have the lowest revenue and profit.

To increase chances of high profit margins, mvoies should be released close to the start of high revenue months.

Conclusions¶

Movie Release month¶

  1. For optimal movie performance, producers should target their release dates on the months of:
    • May
    • June
    • December
    • July
  2. Whenever possible, avoid releasing movies in the months:
    • January
    • September
    • August

Best performing Directors¶

  1. Highest Profit Margins directors To produce Movies with Highest Profit Margins, top 3 directors to use are:

    • Kyle Balda and Pierre Coffin
    • Lee Unkrich
    • Andrew Stanton and Lee Unkrich

  2. Lowest Budget Directors When the budget is not high and the desired movie performance is high, directors below can deliver high performing movies at the lowest cost:

    • Roger Allers and Rob Minkoff
    • Pierre Coffin and Chris Renaud
    • Kyle Balda and Pierre Coffin

  3. Popularity When marketing other movies within the platform, other factors of the movie can be ignored and popularity of the movie used for advertisement is prioritized. In these scenario, the below director can deliver:

    • Colin Trevorrow
    • Kyle Balda and Pierre Coffin
    • Pete Docter

Taking all the observations from point 1 to 3, Kyle Balda and Pierre Coffin can deliver high performing movie on low budget with high profit margin and popularity.

Limitations¶

  1. Individual director contribution to the film performance when a film is produced by more than one directors has not been calculated. Whenever a film is produced by more than one directors, my analysis treats multiple directors as it does with individual directors. In most instances, these directors have produced other films by themselves but my analysis does not factor in their contribution in other films where they produced a film with other directors.

  2. The conclusions on best performing directors is based on top 10 movies per profit. This has ignored the fact that there can be higher performing directors for the popularity and budget when we eliminate the best 10 directors by profit condition.

  3. Recommendations on film performance on the conclusion section above has ignored the fact that a combination of directors that have not worked together before can produce a high performing film.

  4. Minimum number of film produced by director to be considered high performing has not been set. In the event that a director produced one high performing film, they will appear on the conclusion. In real life, this will not be accurate because:

    • The movie might have been released in months associated with high performance.
    • The director might have worked with high performing cast
    • Film story line might have been top notch

To achieve accurate conclusion, minimum number of film produced will atleast ensure that the actor has dealt with multiple scenarios and still performs.
